 and supported religious houses, and fed the poor - providing for his soul and emphasising his aura of authority. In these areas, he ranks alongside many other medieval rulers. The book also presents a major reassessment of the king's dispute with the church, when England was subject to a generalinterdict, and the king was excommunicate, the severest sanctions the medieval church could impose. It reveals the lasting damage to the king's reputation, but also shows how royal religious activity continued whilst king and pope were at loggerheads. Furthermore, despite his vilification since his death, there were those prepared to honour John's memory, during the medieval period and beyond. Dr Paul Webster is a Teaching Associate at CardiffUniversity, in the Cardiff School of History, Archaeology and Religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aKing John.  aactions.  aattitude.  aauthority.  achapels.  achaplains.  achurch dispute.  achurch.  aexcommunication.  afaith.  ahistorical context.  aholy relics.  ainterdict.  amasses.  amedieval church.  amedieval period.  amedieval rulers.  amedieval writers.  amemory.  apersonal religion.  areligion.  areligious houses.  areputation.  aroyal religious activity.  asaints.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782045120?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782045120423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782045120/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles